# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scipy-library
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **interpolation** is a type of estimation, a method of constructing (finding) new data points based on the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In engineering and science, one often has a number of data points, obtained by sampling or experimentation, which represent the values of a function for a limited number of values of the independent variable.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] It is often required to **interpolate**; that is, estimate the value of that function for an intermediate value of the independent variable.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] A closely related problem is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Suppose the formula for some given function is known, but too complicated to evaluate efficiently.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] A few data points from the original function can be interpolated to produce a simpler function which is still fairly close to the original.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The resulting gain in simplicity may outweigh the loss from interpolation error and give better performance in calculation process.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] As an example we will use points from the equation $f(x)=sin(x)$ to demonstrate various interpolation methods.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] We describe some methods of interpolation, differing in such properties as: accuracy, cost, number of data points needed, and smoothness of the resulting interpolant function.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The simplest interpolation method is to locate the nearest data value, and assign the same value.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In simple problems, this method is unlikely to be used, as linear interpolation (see below) is almost as easy, but in higher-dimensional multivariate interpolation, this could be a favourable choice for its speed and simplicity.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] One of the simplest methods is linear interpolation (sometimes known as lerp).
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Consider the above example of estimating *f*(2.5).
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Linear interpolation is quick and easy, but it is not very precise.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Another disadvantage is that the interpolant is not differentiable at the point *x**k*.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The following error estimate shows that linear interpolation is not very precise.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Denote the function which we want to interpolate by *g*, and suppose that *x* lies between *x**a* and *x**b* and that *g* is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In words, the error is proportional to the square of the distance between the data points.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The error in some other methods, including polynomial interpolation and spline interpolation (described below), is proportional to higher powers of the distance between the data points.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] These methods also produce smoother interpolants.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation is a generalization of linear interpolation.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Note that the linear interpolant is a linear function.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] We now replace this interpolant with a polynomial of higher degree.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Generally, if we have *n* data points, there is exactly one polynomial of degree at most *n*−1 going through all the data points.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The interpolation error is proportional to the distance between the data points to the power *n*.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Furthermore, the interpolant is a polynomial and thus infinitely differentiable.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] So, we see that polynomial interpolation overcomes most of the problems of linear interpolation.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] However, polynomial interpolation also has some disadvantages.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Calculating the interpolating polynomial is computationally expensive (see computational complexity) compared to linear interpolation.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Furthermore, polynomial interpolation may exhibit oscillatory artifacts, especially at the end points (see Runge's phenomenon).
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation can estimate local maxima and minima that are outside the range of the samples, unlike linear interpolation.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] However, these maxima and minima may exceed the theoretical range of the function; for example, a function that is always positive may have an interpolant with negative values, and whose inverse therefore contains false vertical asymptotes.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] More generally, the shape of the resulting curve, especially for very high or low values of the independent variable, may be contrary to commonsense; that is, to what is known about the experimental system which has generated the data points.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] These disadvantages can be reduced by using spline interpolation or restricting attention to Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Linear interpolation uses a linear function for each of intervals [*x**k*,*x**k+1*].
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Spline interpolation uses low-degree polynomials in each of the intervals, and chooses the polynomial pieces such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The resulting function is called a spline.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] For instance, the natural cubic spline is piecewise cubic and twice continuously differentiable.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Furthermore, its second derivative is zero at the end points.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Like polynomial interpolation, spline interpolation incurs a smaller error than linear interpolation, while the interpolant is smoother and easier to evaluate than the high-degree polynomials used in polynomial interpolation.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] However, the global nature of the basis functions leads to ill-conditioning.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] This is completely mitigated by using splines of compact support, such as are implemented in Boost.Math and discussed in Kress.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Depending on the underlying discretisation of fields, different interpolants may be required.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In contrast to other interpolation methods, which estimate functions on target points, mimetic interpolation evaluates the integral of fields on target lines, areas or volumes, depending on the type of field (scalar, vector, pseudo-vector or pseudo-scalar).
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] A key feature of mimetic interpolation is that vector calculus identities are satisfied, including Stokes' theorem and the divergence theorem.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] As a result, mimetic interpolation conserves line, area and volume integrals.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Conservation of line integrals might be desirable when interpolating the electric field, for instance, since the line integral gives the electric potential difference at the endpoints of the integration path.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation ensures that the error of estimating the line integral of an electric field is the same as the error obtained by interpolating the potential at the end points of the integration path, regardless of the length of the integration path.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Linear, bilinear and trilinear interpolation are also considered mimetic, even if it is the field values that are conserved (not the integral of the field).
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Apart from linear interpolation, area weighted interpolation can be considered one of the first mimetic interpolation methods to have been developed.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The Theory of Functional Connections (TFC) is a mathematical framework specifically developed for functional interpolation.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Given any interpolant that satisfies a set of constraints, TFC derives a functional that represents the entire family of interpolants satisfying those constraints, including those that are discontinuous or partially defined.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] These functionals identify the subspace of functions where the solution to a constrained optimization problem resides.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Consequently, TFC transforms constrained optimization problems into equivalent unconstrained formulations.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] This transformation has proven highly effective in the solution of differential equations.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] TFC achieves this by constructing a constrained functional (a function of a free function), that inherently satisfies given constraints regardless of the expression of the free function.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] This simplifies solving various types of equations and significantly improves the efficiency and accuracy of methods like Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs).
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] TFC offers advantages over traditional methods like Lagrange multipliers and spectral methods by directly addressing constraints analytically and avoiding iterative procedures, although it cannot currently handle inequality constraints.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Interpolation is a common way to approximate functions.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Given a function $f:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ with a set of points $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}\in [a,b]$ one can form a function $s:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ such that $f(x_{i})=s(x_{i})$ for $i=1,2,\dots ,n$ (that is, that s interpolates f at these points).
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In general, an interpolant need not be a good approximation, but there are well known and often reasonable conditions where it will.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] For example, if $f\in C^{4}([a,b])$ (four times continuously differentiable) then cubic spline interpolation has an error bound given by $\|f-s\|_{\infty }\leq C\|f^{(4)}\|_{\infty }h^{4}$ where $h\max _{i=1,2,\dots ,n-1}|x_{i+1}-x_{i}|$ and C is a constant.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Gaussian process is a powerful non-linear interpolation tool.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Many popular interpolation tools are actually equivalent to particular Gaussian processes.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Gaussian processes can be used not only for fitting an interpolant that passes exactly through the given data points but also for regression; that is, for fitting a curve through noisy data.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In the geostatistics community Gaussian process regression is also known as Kriging.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW) is a spatial interpolation method that estimates values based on nearby data points, with closer points having more influence.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] It uses an inverse power law for weighting, where higher power values emphasize local effects, while lower values create a smoother surface.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] IDW is widely used in GIS, meteorology, and environmental modeling for its simplicity but may produce artifacts in clustered or uneven data.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Other forms of interpolation can be constructed by picking a different class of interpolants.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] For instance, rational interpolation is **interpolation** by rational functions using Padé approximant, and trigonometric interpolation is interpolation by trigonometric polynomials using Fourier series.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula can be used if the number of data points is infinite or if the function to be interpolated has compact support.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Sometimes, we know not only the value of the function that we want to interpolate, at some points, but also its derivative.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] This leads to Hermite interpolation problems.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] When each data point is itself a function, it can be useful to see the interpolation problem as a partial advection problem between each data point.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] This idea leads to the displacement interpolation problem used in transportation theory.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Multivariate interpolation is the interpolation of functions of more than one variable.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Methods include nearest-neighbor interpolation, bilinear interpolation and bicubic interpolation in two dimensions, and trilinear interpolation in three dimensions.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] They can be applied to gridded or scattered data.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation generalizes to n dimensional spaces where $n>3$ .
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In this application there is a specific requirement that the harmonic content of the original signal be preserved without creating aliased harmonic content of the original signal above the original Nyquist limit of the signal (that is, above fs/2 of the original signal sample rate).
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] An early and fairly elementary discussion on this subject can be found in Rabiner and Crochiere's book *Multirate Digital Signal Processing*.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The term *extrapolation* is used to find data points outside the range of known data points.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In curve fitting problems, the constraint that the interpolant has to go exactly through the data points is relaxed.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] It is only required to approach the data points as closely as possible (within some other constraints).
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] This requires parameterizing the potential interpolants and having some way of measuring the error.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] In the simplest case this leads to least squares approximation.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] Approximation theory studies how to find the best approximation to a given function by another function from some predetermined class, and how good this approximation is.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] This clearly yields a bound on how well the interpolant can approximate the unknown function.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] If we consider x as a variable in a topological space, and the function $f(x)$ mapping to a Banach space, then the problem is treated as "interpolation of operators".
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] The classical results about interpolation of operators are the Riesz–Thorin theorem and the Marcinkiewicz theorem.
[src:scipy-library/interpolation] There are also many other subsequent results.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis finds application in all fields of engineering and the physical sciences, and in the 21st century also the life and social sciences like economics, medicine, business and even the arts.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Current growth in computing power has enabled the use of more complex numerical analysis, providing detailed and realistic mathematical models in science and engineering.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Before modern computers, numerical methods often relied on hand interpolation formulas, using data from large printed tables.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Since the mid-20th century, computers calculate the required functions instead, but many of the same formulas continue to be used in software algorithms.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The numerical point of view goes back to the earliest mathematical writings.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] A tablet from the Yale Babylonian Collection (YBC 7289), gives a sexagesimal numerical approximation of the square root of 2, the length of the diagonal in a unit square.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis continues this long tradition: rather than giving exact symbolic answers translated into digits and applicable only to real-world measurements, approximate solutions within specified error bounds are used.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The field of numerical analysis predates the invention of modern computers by many centuries.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Linear interpolation was already in use more than 2000 years ago.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Many great mathematicians of the past were preoccupied by numerical analysis, as is obvious from the names of important algorithms like Newton's method, Lagrange interpolation polynomial, Gaussian elimination, or Euler's method.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The origins of modern numerical analysis are often linked to a 1947 paper by John von Neumann and Herman Goldstine, but others consider modern numerical analysis to go back to work by E.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] To facilitate computations by hand, large books were produced with formulas and tables of data such as interpolation points and function coefficients.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Using these tables, often calculated out to 16 decimal places or more for some functions, one could look up values to plug into the formulas given and achieve very good numerical estimates of some functions.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The canonical work in the field is the NIST publication edited by Abramowitz and Stegun, a 1000-plus page book of a very large number of commonly used formulas and functions and their values at many points.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The function values are no longer very useful when a computer is available, but the large listing of formulas can still be very handy.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The mechanical calculator was also developed as a tool for hand computation.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] These calculators evolved into electronic computers in the 1940s, and it was then found that these computers were also useful for administrative purposes.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] But the invention of the computer also influenced the field of numerical analysis, since now longer and more complicated calculations could be done.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The Leslie Fox Prize for Numerical Analysis was initiated in 1985 by the Institute of Mathematics and its Applications.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Direct methods compute the solution to a problem in a finite number of steps.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] These methods would give the precise answer if they were performed in infinite precision arithmetic.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Examples include Gaussian elimination, the QR factorization method for solving systems of linear equations, and the simplex method of linear programming.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] In practice, finite precision is used and the result is an approximation of the true solution (assuming stability).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] In contrast to direct methods, iterative methods are not expected to terminate in a finite number of steps, even if infinite precision were possible.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Starting from an initial guess, iterative methods form successive approximations that converge to the exact solution only in the limit.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] A convergence test, often involving the residual, is specified in order to decide when a sufficiently accurate solution has (hopefully) been found.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Even using infinite precision arithmetic these methods would not reach the solution within a finite number of steps (in general).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Examples include Newton's method, the bisection method, and Jacobi iteration.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] In computational matrix algebra, iterative methods are generally needed for large problems.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Iterative methods are more common than direct methods in numerical analysis.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Some methods are direct in principle but are usually used as though they were not, e.g.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] GMRES and the conjugate gradient method.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] For these methods the number of steps needed to obtain the exact solution is so large that an approximation is accepted in the same manner as for an iterative method.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] For the iterative method, apply the bisection method to *f*(*x*) = 3*x*3 − 24.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] From this table it can be concluded that the solution is between 1.875 and 2.0625.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The algorithm might return any number in that range with an error less than 0.2.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Ill-conditioned problem: Take the function *f*(*x*) = 1/(*x* − 1).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Evaluating *f*(*x*) near *x* = 1 is an ill-conditioned problem.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Well-conditioned problem: By contrast, evaluating the same function *f*(*x*) = 1/(*x* − 1) near *x* = 10 is a well-conditioned problem.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Furthermore, continuous problems must sometimes be replaced by a discrete problem whose solution is known to approximate that of the continuous problem; this process is called 'discretization'.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] For example, the solution of a differential equation is a function.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] This function must be represented by a finite amount of data, for instance by its value at a finite number of points at its domain, even though this domain is a continuum.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The study of errors forms an important part of numerical analysis.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] There are several ways in which error can be introduced in the solution of the problem.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Round-off errors arise because it is impossible to represent all real numbers exactly on a machine with finite memory (which is what all practical digital computers are).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Truncation errors are committed when an iterative method is terminated or a mathematical procedure is approximated and the approximate solution differs from the exact solution.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Similarly, discretization induces a discretization error because the solution of the discrete problem does not coincide with the solution of the continuous problem.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] In the example above to compute the solution of $3x^{3}+4=28$ , after ten iterations, the calculated root is roughly 1.99.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Therefore, the truncation error is roughly 0.01.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Once an error is generated, it propagates through the calculation.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] For example, the operation + on a computer is inexact.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] A calculation of the type ⁠ $a+b+c+d+e$ ⁠ is even more inexact.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] A truncation error is created when a mathematical procedure is approximated.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] To integrate a function exactly, an infinite sum of regions must be found, but numerically only a finite sum of regions can be found, and hence the approximation of the exact solution.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Similarly, to differentiate a function, the differential element approaches zero, but numerically only a nonzero value of the differential element can be chosen.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] An algorithm is called *numerically stable* if an error, whatever its cause, does not grow to be much larger during the calculation.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] This happens if the problem is *well-conditioned*, meaning that the solution changes by only a small amount if the problem data are changed by a small amount.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] To the contrary, if a problem is 'ill-conditioned', then any small error in the data will grow to be a large error.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Both the original problem and the algorithm used to solve that problem can be well-conditioned or ill-conditioned, and any combination is possible.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] So an algorithm that solves a well-conditioned problem may be either numerically stable or numerically unstable.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] An art of numerical analysis is to find a stable algorithm for solving a well-posed mathematical problem.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The field of numerical analysis includes many sub-disciplines.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] One of the simplest problems is the evaluation of a function at a given point.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The most straightforward approach, of just plugging in the number in the formula is sometimes not very efficient.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] For polynomials, a better approach is using the Horner scheme, since it reduces the necessary number of multiplications and additions.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Generally, it is important to estimate and control round-off errors arising from the use of floating-point arithmetic.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Interpolation solves the following problem: given the value of some unknown function at a number of points, what value does that function have at some other point between the given points?
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Extrapolation is very similar to interpolation, except that now the value of the unknown function at a point which is outside the given points must be found.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Regression is also similar, but it takes into account that the data are imprecise.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Given some points, and a measurement of the value of some function at these points (with an error), the unknown function can be found.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The least squares-method is one way to achieve this.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Another fundamental problem is computing the solution of some given equation.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Two cases are commonly distinguished, depending on whether the equation is linear or not.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] For instance, the equation $2x+5=3$ is linear while $2x^{2}+5=3$ is not.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Much effort has been put in the development of methods for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Standard direct methods, i.e., methods that use some matrix decomposition are Gaussian elimination, LU decomposition, Cholesky decomposition for symmetric (or hermitian) and positive-definite matrix, and QR decomposition for non-square matrices.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Iterative methods such as the Jacobi method, Gauss–Seidel method, successive over-relaxation and conjugate gradient method are usually preferred for large systems.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] General iterative methods can be developed using a matrix splitting.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Root-finding algorithms are used to solve nonlinear equations (they are so named since a root of a function is an argument for which the function yields zero).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] If the function is differentiable and the derivative is known, then Newton's method is a popular choice.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Linearization is another technique for solving nonlinear equations.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Several important problems can be phrased in terms of eigenvalue decompositions or singular value decompositions.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] For instance, the spectral image compression algorithm is based on the singular value decomposition.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The corresponding tool in statistics is called principal component analysis.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Optimization problems ask for the point at which a given function is maximized (or minimized).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Often, the point also has to satisfy some constraints.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The field of optimization is further split in several subfields, depending on the form of the objective function and the constraint.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] For instance, linear programming deals with the case that both the objective function and the constraints are linear.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] A famous method in linear programming is the simplex method.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The method of Lagrange multipliers can be used to reduce optimization problems with constraints to unconstrained optimization problems.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Numerical integration, in some instances also known as numerical quadrature, asks for the value of a definite integral.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Popular methods use one of the Newton–Cotes formulas (like the midpoint rule or Simpson's rule) or Gaussian quadrature.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] These methods rely on a "divide and conquer" strategy, whereby an integral on a relatively large set is broken down into integrals on smaller sets.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] In higher dimensions, where these methods become prohibitively expensive in terms of computational effort, one may use Monte Carlo or quasi-Monte Carlo methods (see Monte Carlo integration), or, in modestly large dimensions, the method of sparse grids.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis is also concerned with computing (in an approximate way) the solution of differential equations, both ordinary differential equations and partial differential equations.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Partial differential equations are solved by first discretizing the equation, bringing it into a finite-dimensional subspace.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] This can be done by a finite element method, a finite difference method, or (particularly in engineering) a finite volume method.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The theoretical justification of these methods often involves theorems from functional analysis.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] This reduces the problem to the solution of an algebraic equation.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Since the late twentieth century, most algorithms are implemented in a variety of programming languages.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The Netlib repository contains various collections of software routines for numerical problems, mostly in Fortran and C.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Commercial products implementing many different numerical algorithms include the IMSL and NAG libraries; a free-software alternative is the GNU Scientific Library.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Over the years the Royal Statistical Society published numerous algorithms in its *Applied Statistics* (code for these "AS" functions is here); ACM similarly, in its *Transactions on Mathematical Software* ("TOMS" code is here).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] The Naval Surface Warfare Center several times published its *Library of Mathematics Subroutines* (code here).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] There are several popular numerical computing applications such as MATLAB, TK Solver, S-PLUS, and IDL as well as free and open-source alternatives such as FreeMat, Scilab, GNU Octave (similar to Matlab), and IT++ (a C++ library).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] There are also programming languages such as R (similar to S-PLUS), Julia, and Python with libraries such as NumPy, SciPy and SymPy.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Performance varies widely: while vector and matrix operations are usually fast, scalar loops may vary in speed by more than an order of magnitude.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Many computer algebra systems such as Mathematica also benefit from the availability of arbitrary-precision arithmetic which can provide more accurate results.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Also, any spreadsheet software can be used to solve simple problems relating to numerical analysis.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-analysis] Excel, for example, has hundreds of available functions, including for matrices, which may be used in conjunction with its built in "solver".
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] In analysis, **numerical integration** comprises a broad family of algorithms for calculating the numerical value of a definite integral.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The term **numerical quadrature** (often abbreviated to **quadrature**) is more or less a synonym for "numerical integration", especially as applied to one-dimensional integrals.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Some authors refer to numerical integration over more than one dimension as **cubature**; others take "quadrature" to include higher-dimensional integration.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] If *f*(*x*) is a smooth function integrated over a small number of dimensions, and the domain of integration is bounded, there are many methods for approximating the integral to the desired precision.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Numerical integration has roots in the geometrical problem of finding a square with the same area as a given plane figure (*quadrature* or *squaring*), as in the quadrature of the circle.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The term is also sometimes used to describe the numerical solution of differential equations.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] A formula for the integrand may be known, but it may be difficult or impossible to find an antiderivative that is an elementary function.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] An example of such an integrand is *f* (*x*) = exp(−*x*2), the antiderivative of which (the error function, times a constant) cannot be written in elementary form .
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] It may be possible to find an antiderivative symbolically, but it may be easier to compute a numerical approximation than to compute the antiderivative.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] That may be the case if the antiderivative is given as an infinite series or product, or if its evaluation requires a special function that is not available.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The term "numerical integration" first appears in 1915 in the publication *A Course in Interpolation and Numeric Integration for the Mathematical Laboratory* by David Gibb.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] "Quadrature" is a historical mathematical term that means calculating area.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Quadrature problems have served as one of the main sources of mathematical analysis.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Mathematicians of Ancient Greece, according to the Pythagorean doctrine, understood calculation of area as the process of constructing geometrically a square having the same area (*squaring*) — that is why the process was named "quadrature".
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Examples include quadrature of the circle, Lune of Hippocrates, and the treatise *Quadrature of the Parabola*.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] This construction must be performed only by means of compass and straightedge.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The ancient Babylonians used the trapezoidal rule to integrate the motion of Jupiter along the ecliptic.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] For a quadrature of a rectangle with the sides *a* and *b* it is necessary to construct a square with the side $x={\sqrt {ab}}$ (the geometric mean of *a* and *b*).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] For this purpose it is possible to use the following fact: if we draw the circle with the sum of *a* and *b* as the diameter, then the height BH (from a point of their connection to crossing with a circle) equals their geometric mean.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The similar geometrical construction solves a problem of a quadrature for a parallelogram and a triangle.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Problems of quadrature for curvilinear figures are much more difficult.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the circle with compass and straightedge had been proved in the 19th century to be impossible.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Nevertheless, for some figures (for example the lune of Hippocrates) a quadrature can be performed.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The quadratures of a sphere surface and a parabola segment done by Archimedes became the highest achievement of the antique analysis.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] To prove the results, Archimedes used the method of exhaustion of Eudoxus.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] In medieval Europe the quadrature meant calculation of area by any method.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] More often the method of indivisibles was used; it was less rigorous, but more simple and powerful.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] John Wallis algebrised this method: he wrote in his *Arithmetica Infinitorum* (1656) series that we now call the definite integral, and he calculated their values.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Isaac Barrow and James Gregory made further progress: quadratures for some algebraic curves and spirals.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Christiaan Huygens successfully performed a quadrature of some solids of revolution.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the hyperbola by Saint-Vincent and de Sarasa provided a new function, the natural logarithm, of critical importance.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] With the invention of integral calculus came a universal method for area calculation.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] In response, the term "quadrature" has become traditional, and instead the modern phrase "*computation of a univariate definite integral*" is more common.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] A **quadrature rule** is an approximation of the definite integral of a function, usually stated as a weighted sum of function values at specified points within the domain of integration.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Numerical integration methods can generally be described as combining evaluations of the integrand to get an approximation to the integral.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The integrand is evaluated at a finite set of points called ***integration points*** and a weighted sum of these values is used to approximate the integral.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The integration points and weights depend on the specific method used and the accuracy required from the approximation.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] An important part of the analysis of any numerical integration method is to study the behavior of the approximation error as a function of the number of integrand evaluations.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] A method that yields a small error for a small number of evaluations is usually considered superior.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Reducing the number of evaluations of the integrand reduces the number of arithmetic operations involved, and therefore reduces the total error.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Also, each evaluation takes time, and the integrand may be arbitrarily complicated.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] A "brute force" kind of numerical integration can be done, if the integrand is reasonably well-behaved (i.e. piecewise continuous and of bounded variation), by evaluating the integrand with very small increments.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] This simplest method approximates the function by a step function (a piecewise constant function, or a segmented polynomial of degree zero) that passes through the point ${\textstyle \left({\frac {a+b}{2}},f\left({\frac {a+b}{2}}\right)\right)}$ .
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] A large class of quadrature rules can be derived by constructing interpolating functions that are easy to integrate.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Typically these interpolating functions are polynomials.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] In practice, since polynomials of very high degree tend to oscillate wildly, only polynomials of low degree are used, typically linear and quadratic.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The interpolating function may be a straight line (an affine function, i.e. a polynomial of degree 1) passing through the points $\left(a,f(a)\right)$ and $\left(b,f(b)\right)$ .
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] For either one of these rules, we can make a more accurate approximation by breaking up the interval $[a,b]$ into some number n of subintervals, computing an approximation for each subinterval, then adding up all the results.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] This is called a *composite rule*, *extended rule*, or *iterated rule*.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] where the subintervals have the form $[a+kh,a+(k+1)h]\subset [a,b],$ with ${\textstyle h={\frac {b-a}{n}}}$ and $k=0,\ldots ,n-1.$ Here we used subintervals of the same length h but one could also use intervals of varying length $\left(h_{k}\right)_{k}$ .
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Interpolation with polynomials evaluated at equally spaced points in $[a,b]$ yields the Newton–Cotes formulas, of which the rectangle rule and the trapezoidal rule are examples.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Simpson's rule, which is based on a polynomial of order 2, is also a Newton–Cotes formula.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Quadrature rules with equally spaced points have the very convenient property of *nesting*.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The corresponding rule with each interval subdivided includes all the current points, so those integrand values can be re-used.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] If we allow the intervals between interpolation points to vary, we find another group of quadrature formulas, such as the Gaussian quadrature formulas.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] A Gaussian quadrature rule is typically more accurate than a Newton–Cotes rule that uses the same number of function evaluations, if the integrand is smooth (i.e., if it is sufficiently differentiable).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Other quadrature methods with varying intervals include Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature (also called Fejér quadrature) methods, which do nest.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Gaussian quadrature rules do not nest, but the related Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formulas do.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Adaptive quadrature is a numerical integration method in which the integral of a function $f(x)$ is approximated using static quadrature rules on adaptively refined subintervals of the region of integration.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Generally, adaptive algorithms are just as efficient and effective as traditional algorithms for "well behaved" integrands, but are also effective for "badly behaved" integrands for which traditional algorithms may fail.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The accuracy of a quadrature rule of the Newton–Cotes type is generally a function of the number of evaluation points.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The result is usually more accurate as the number of evaluation points increases, or, equivalently, as the width of the step size between the points decreases.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] It is natural to ask what the result would be if the step size were allowed to approach zero.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] This can be answered by extrapolating the result from two or more nonzero step sizes, using series acceleration methods such as Richardson extrapolation.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The extrapolation function may be a polynomial or rational function.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Extrapolation methods are described in more detail by Stoer and Bulirsch (Section 3.4) and are implemented in many of the routines in the QUADPACK library.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] where the supremum was used to approximate.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Hence, if we approximate the integral ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}$ by the quadrature rule $(b-a)f(a)$ our error is no greater than the right hand side of **1**.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] We can convert this into an error analysis for the Riemann sum, giving an upper bound of ${\frac {n^{-1}}{2}}\sup _{0\leq x\leq 1}\left|f'(x)\right|$ for the error term of that particular approximation.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] (Note that this is precisely the error we calculated for the example $f(x)=x$ .) Using more derivatives, and by tweaking the quadrature, we can do a similar error analysis using a Taylor series (using a partial sum with remainder term) for *f*.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] This error analysis gives a strict upper bound on the error, if the derivatives of *f* are available.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] This integration method can be combined with interval arithmetic to produce computer proofs and *verified* calculations.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Several methods exist for approximate integration over unbounded intervals.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The standard technique involves specially derived quadrature rules, such as Gauss-Hermite quadrature for integrals on the whole real line and Gauss-Laguerre quadrature for integrals on the positive reals.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The quadrature rules discussed so far are all designed to compute one-dimensional integrals.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] To compute integrals in multiple dimensions, one approach is to phrase the multiple integral as repeated one-dimensional integrals by applying Fubini's theorem (the tensor product rule).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] This approach requires the function evaluations to grow exponentially as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Three methods are known to overcome this so-called *curse of dimensionality*.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] A great many additional techniques for forming multidimensional cubature integration rules for a variety of weighting functions are given in the monograph by Stroud.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Integration on the sphere has been reviewed by Hesse et al.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Monte Carlo methods and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are easy to apply to multi-dimensional integrals.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] They may yield greater accuracy for the same number of function evaluations than repeated integrations using one-dimensional methods.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] A large class of useful Monte Carlo methods are the so-called Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms, which include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and Gibbs sampling.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Sparse grids were originally developed by Smolyak for the quadrature of high-dimensional functions.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The method is always based on a one-dimensional quadrature rule, but performs a more sophisticated combination of univariate results.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] However, whereas the tensor product rule guarantees that the weights of all of the cubature points will be positive if the weights of the quadrature points were positive, Smolyak's rule does not guarantee that the weights will all be positive.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Bayesian quadrature is a statistical approach to the numerical problem of computing integrals and falls under the field of probabilistic numerics.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] It can provide a full handling of the uncertainty over the solution of the integral expressed as a Gaussian process posterior variance.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] can be reduced to an initial value problem for an ordinary differential equation by applying the first part of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Numerical methods for ordinary differential equations, such as Runge–Kutta methods, can be applied to the restated problem and thus be used to evaluate the integral.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] For instance, the standard fourth-order Runge–Kutta method applied to the differential equation yields Simpson's rule from above.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The differential equation $F'(x)=f(x)$ has a special form: the right-hand side contains only the independent variable (here x ) and not the dependent variable (here F ).
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] This simplifies the theory and algorithms considerably.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] The problem of evaluating integrals is thus best studied in its own right.
[src:scipy-library/numerical-integration] Conversely, the term "quadrature" may also be used for the solution of differential equations: "solving by quadrature" or "reduction to quadrature" means expressing its solution in terms of integrals.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] The Python programming language was not originally designed for numerical computing, but attracted the attention of the scientific and engineering community early on.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] In 1995 the special interest group (SIG) *matrix-sig* was founded with the aim of defining an array computing package; among its members was Python designer and maintainer Guido van Rossum, who extended Python's syntax (in particular the indexing syntax) to make array computing easier.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Hugunin, a graduate student at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), joined the Corporation for National Research Initiatives (CNRI) in 1997 to work on JPython, leaving Paul Dubois of Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL) to take over as maintainer.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Other early contributors include David Ascher, Konrad Hinsen and Travis Oliphant.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] A new package called *Numarray* was written as a more flexible replacement for Numeric.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Numarray had faster operations for large arrays, but was slower than Numeric on small ones, so for a time both packages were used in parallel for different use cases.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] The last version of Numeric (v24.2) was released on 11 November 2005, while the last version of numarray (v1.5.2) was released on 24 August 2006.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] There was a desire to get Numeric into the Python standard library, but Guido van Rossum decided that the code was not maintainable in its state then.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] In early 2005, NumPy developer Travis Oliphant wanted to unify the community around a single array package and ported Numarray's features to Numeric, releasing the result as NumPy 1.0 in 2006.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] To avoid installing the large SciPy package just to get an array object, this new package was separated and called NumPy.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Support for Python 3 was added in 2011 with NumPy version 1.5.0.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] In 2011, PyPy started development on an implementation of the NumPy API for PyPy.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] As of 2023, it is not yet fully compatible with NumPy.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] NumPy targets the CPython reference implementation of Python, which is a non-optimizing bytecode interpreter.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Mathematical algorithms written for this version of Python often run much slower than compiled equivalents due to the absence of compiler optimization.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] NumPy addresses the slowness problem partly by providing multidimensional arrays and functions and operators that operate efficiently on arrays; using these requires rewriting some code, mostly inner loops, using NumPy.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Using NumPy in Python gives functionality comparable to MATLAB since they are both interpreted, and they both allow the user to write fast programs as long as most operations work on arrays or matrices instead of scalars.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] In comparison, MATLAB boasts a large number of additional toolboxes, notably Simulink, whereas NumPy is intrinsically integrated with Python, a more modern and complete programming language.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Moreover, complementary Python packages are available; SciPy is a library that adds more MATLAB-like functionality and Matplotlib is a plotting package that provides MATLAB-like plotting functionality.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Although MATLAB can perform sparse matrix operations, NumPy alone cannot perform such operations and requires the use of the scipy.sparse library.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Internally, both MATLAB and NumPy rely on BLAS and LAPACK for efficient linear algebra computations.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Python bindings of the widely used computer vision library OpenCV utilize NumPy arrays to store and operate on data.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Since images with multiple channels are simply represented as three-dimensional arrays, indexing, slicing or masking with other arrays are very efficient ways to access specific pixels of an image.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] The NumPy array as universal data structure in OpenCV for images, extracted feature points, filter kernels and many more vastly simplifies the programming workflow and debugging.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Importantly, many NumPy operations release the global interpreter lock, which allows for multithreaded processing.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] NumPy also provides a C API, which allows Python code to interoperate with external libraries written in low-level languages.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] The core functionality of NumPy is its "ndarray", for *n*-dimensional array, data structure.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] These arrays are strided views on memory.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] In contrast to Python's built-in list data structure, these arrays are homogeneously typed: all elements of a single array must be of the same type.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Such arrays can also be views into memory buffers allocated by C/C++, Python, and Fortran extensions to the CPython interpreter without the need to copy data around, giving a degree of compatibility with existing numerical libraries.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] This functionality is exploited by the SciPy package, which wraps a number of such libraries (notably BLAS and LAPACK).
[src:scipy-library/numpy] NumPy has built-in support for memory-mapped ndarrays.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Inserting or appending entries to an array is not as trivially possible as it is with Python's lists.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] The `np.pad(...)` routine to extend arrays actually creates new arrays of the desired shape and padding values, copies the given array into the new one and returns it.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] NumPy's `np.concatenate([a1,a2])` operation does not actually link the two arrays but returns a new one, filled with the entries from both given arrays in sequence.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Reshaping the dimensionality of an array with `np.reshape(...)` is only possible as long as the number of elements in the array does not change.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] These circumstances originate from the fact that NumPy's arrays must be views on contiguous memory buffers.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Runtime compilation of numerical code has been implemented by several groups to avoid these problems; open source solutions that interoperate with NumPy include numexpr and Numba.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Cython and Pythran are static-compiling alternatives to these.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Many modern large-scale scientific computing applications have requirements that exceed the capabilities of the NumPy arrays.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] For example, NumPy arrays are usually loaded into a computer's memory, which might have insufficient capacity for the analysis of large datasets.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Further, NumPy operations are executed on a single CPU.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] However, many linear algebra operations can be accelerated by executing them on clusters of CPUs or on specialized hardware, such as GPUs and TPUs, which many deep learning applications rely on.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] As a result, several alternative array implementations have arisen in the scientific python ecosystem over the recent years, such as Dask for distributed arrays and TensorFlow or JAX for computations on GPUs.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Because of its popularity, these often implement a subset of NumPy's API or mimic it, so that users can change their array implementation with minimal changes to their code required.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] A library named CuPy, accelerated by Nvidia's CUDA framework, has also shown potential for faster computing, being a 'drop-in replacement' of NumPy.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] NumPy is conventionally imported as `np`.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Functional Python and vectorized NumPy version.
[src:scipy-library/numpy] Quickly wrap native code for faster scripts.
[src:scipy-library/optimize] SciPy `optimize` provides functions for minimizing (or maximizing) objective functions, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:scipy-library/optimize] It includes solvers for nonlinear problems (with support for both local and global optimization algorithms), linear programming, constrained and nonlinear least-squares, root finding, and curve fitting.
[src:scipy-library/optimize] Quasi-Newton strategies implementing `HessianUpdateStrategy` interface can be used to approximate the Hessian in `minimize` function (available only for the ‘trust-constr’ method).
[src:scipy-library/optimize] The table below lists situations and appropriate methods, along with *asymptotic* convergence rates per iteration (and per function evaluation) for successful convergence to a simple root(*).
[src:scipy-library/optimize] Bisection is the slowest of them all, adding one bit of accuracy for each function evaluation, but is guaranteed to converge.
[src:scipy-library/optimize] The other bracketing methods all (eventually) increase the number of accurate bits by about 50% for every function evaluation.
[src:scipy-library/optimize] The derivative-based methods, all built on `newton`, can converge quite quickly if the initial value is close to the root.
[src:scipy-library/optimize] They can also be applied to functions defined on (a subset of) the complex plane.
[src:scipy-library/optimize] The functions below are not recommended for use in new scripts; all of these methods are accessible via a newer, more consistent interfaces, provided by the interfaces above.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] SciPy contains modules for optimization, linear algebra, integration, interpolation, special functions, fast Fourier transform, signal and image processing, ordinary differential equation solvers and other tasks common in science and engineering.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] SciPy is also a family of conferences for users and developers of these tools: SciPy (in the United States), EuroSciPy (in Europe) and SciPy.in (in India).
[src:scipy-library/scipy] Enthought originated the SciPy conference in the United States and continues to sponsor many of the international conferences as well as host the SciPy website.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] The SciPy library is currently distributed under the BSD license, and its development is sponsored and supported by an open community of developers.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] It is also supported by NumFOCUS, a community foundation for supporting reproducible and accessible science.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] The SciPy package is at the core of Python's scientific computing capabilities.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] The basic data structure used by SciPy is a multidimensional array provided by the NumPy module.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] NumPy provides some functions for linear algebra, Fourier transforms, and random number generation, but not with the generality of the equivalent functions in SciPy.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] NumPy can also be used as an efficient multidimensional container of data with arbitrary datatypes.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] This allows NumPy to seamlessly and speedily integrate with a wide variety of databases.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] Older versions of SciPy used Numeric as an array type, which is now deprecated in favor of the newer NumPy array code.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] In the 1990s, Python was extended to include an array type for numerical computing called Numeric.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] In 2001, Travis Oliphant, Eric Jones, and Pearu Peterson merged code they had written and called the resulting package SciPy.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] The newly created package provided a standard collection of common numerical operations on top of the Numeric array data structure.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] Shortly thereafter, Fernando Pérez released IPython, an enhanced interactive shell widely used in the technical computing community, and John Hunter released the first version of Matplotlib, the 2D plotting library for technical computing.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] Since then the SciPy environment has continued to grow with more packages and tools for technical computing.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] In the scientific literature, SciPy is occasionally referred to as "Scientific Python (SciPy)".
[src:scipy-library/scipy] This is incorrect: the official name of the project is just "SciPy".
[src:scipy-library/scipy] Furthermore, expanding "SciPy" as "Scientific Python" may cause confusion with "ScientificPython", a project led by Konrad Hinsen of Orléans University that was active between 1995 and 2014.
[src:scipy-library/scipy] "Scientific Python" is also used for the related ecosystem of tools.
[src:scipy-library/tutorial-index] SciPy is a collection of mathematical algorithms and convenience functions built on NumPy .
[src:scipy-library/tutorial-index] It adds significant power to Python by providing the user with high-level commands and classes for manipulating and visualizing data.
[src:scipy-library/tutorial-index] SciPy is organized into subpackages covering different scientific computing domains.
[src:scipy-library/tutorial-index] For guidance on organizing and importing functions from SciPy subpackages, refer to the Guidelines for Importing Functions from SciPy.
[src:scipy-library/tutorial-index] For information on support for parallel execution, thread safety, and security see Parallel execution support in SciPy, Thread Safety in SciPy, and Security respectively.
